name: Minted to Skinted: Breakfast for Every Budget

text.text: Minted to Skinted: Breakfast for Every Budget

You often skip it, eat it on the go or spill most of it between the keys of your computer; but breakfast is an absolute banger of a meal, so why not make a fuss over it? Consider for a second the potential it holds: it's the start of the day and you're still so full of hope about what's to come: the sheer possibility gives us the shivers.

From truffled eggs to basic fry ups, there's heaps of tasty fodder to be had at either end of the monetary scale.

tip.text:
A short jaunt along from the Ritz and the Wolseley, this restaurant has some serious matching up to do. Luckily the folk behind Hide have pulled out all the stops to make things swanky af. We'll start with the decor shall we? From the imposing staircase to the floors, chairs, tables, bar tops and private rooms - there is so much wood you can actually smell it. The crockery is fancy, wine decanters are mega, teapots elaborate crystal, and there's even toothpicks in the bathroom.

But you're really here for the food: because wonderchef Ollie Dabbous is in the house; because you've read the reviews and seen *THAT* acorn cake on Insta; and because if the Michelin star is anything to go by, it's gotta be amazing. Your eating options are spread across three floors: 'Below' - where cocktails require an order of bar snacks; 'Ground' which brings suitably fancy dishes; and 'Above' where set menus arrive with all the whimsy of a Brothers Grimm fairytale. Eggs are nestled in hay, charcuterie is wrapped around feathers or bones, and veggies look like they walked out of a painting. If you are partial to pomp (and some genuinely exquisite in-house pastries) then why not save up a couple hundy and give it gander.

text.text:
A short jaunt along from the Ritz, Hide is swanky af. From the imposing staircase to the floors, chairs, tables, bar tops and private rooms - there is so much wood you can actually smell it. The crockery is fancy, wine decanters are mega, teapots elaborate crystal, and there's even toothpicks in the bathroom. You know you can only afford breakfast so in you pop for smoked eel omelette, black pudding, or stunning birch-sap croissants. 

The damage: Truffled scrambled eggs Â£24

tip.text:
This baby was built in 1921 as a hecka fancy car showroom for Wolseley cars. It then became a Barclays bank and now it's a high-brow resto that has us dreaming of another time. Dripping in style and splendour, with huge chandeliers, elaborate floors, and vintage silverware, it makes you want to dress the part too. Decor, service, food - every inch is carefully constructed to make you feel kinda special - and we did.

It's an all-day affair (because the show must go on) so you can breakfast in style, live it up over afternoon tea, have a sumptuous dinner or pop in for a cocktail-heavy night cap. We went for breakfast and were overwhelmed to find the likes of smoked salmon, kippers, haggis AND, best of all, dippy eggs (just like momma used to make them!).

text.text:

Find the likes of smoked salmon, kippers, haggis AND, best of all, dippy eggs (just like momma used to make them!).

The damage: Full English Â£18.75

tip.text:

How about a bowl of smoked almonds and some tuna escabeche with saffron and lime to nibble on under that grand candelabra-lit communal dining table? Their hardshakes are bloody great - try the Pie & Scoop, a combo of Beefeater gin, crÃ¨me de mure liqueur, vanilla ice cream, milk, and cream - it all sounds a bit too tasty to be true.

tip.text:
Another feather in Ottolenghi's cap, Rovi promises all the veg, colour and flavour of its sister restaurants but with more focus on fermentation and grilling over fire - in a huge space with plenty of natural light, red sofas and a free-standing bar in the middle. Fruit and veg comes all the way from a biodynamic farm in Sussex, and a cooperative in East London - so not too many air miles then - and waste will be reduced with nifty tricks like making vinegar out of leftover wine.

As always, Ottolenghi elevates your five-a-day with the likes of braised and smoked carrots with puffed black barley; pan-roasted cauliflower with zaâatar onions; or green beans with roasted grapes. And the worthiness doesn't stop there... the bar serves up cocktails made with house shrubs and all sorts of low intervention wines from small producers. Tidy.

text.text:

Rovi's morning bites are heaven with toasted banana bread, Iranian fritters or various Middle Eastern egg concoctions coming in to play. Wash down with fresh juice or cocktails made with their house shrubs - ooer.

The damage: Jalapeno cornbread, scrambled eggs, avocado, tomato Â£13.50

tip.text:
Three friends (one of whom has a brother called Marcus) put their skills together to found this cafe and events space. With shelves full of plant pots and the little courtyard ideal for an Aperol Spritz on a sunny day.

If you're in the Balham area and you've been to Milk a few too many times then try Brother Marcus out. Open nice 'n' early for your first caffeine hit, and serving up fabulously eggy and rather boozy brunches at the weekend, it's a great all round neighbourhood spot. Go for healthy fruit and muesli breakfast or treat yourself to pancakes. Check it out in the evenings for guest chefs, supper clubs, poetry nights and all sorts of other events.

text.text:

Open nice 'n' early for your first caffeine hit, and serving up fabulously eggy and rather boozy brunches at the weekend, it's a great all round neighbourhood spot. Go for healthy fruit and muesli breakfast or treat yo-self to pancakes.

The damage: Full brekkie Â£10.80

tip.text:
With the team behind Brixton's fine-dining favourite, Salon, on this one, you can be sure the food will be tippity top. The relaxed, hipstery-farmhouse aesthetic remains along with natural wine and menus led by fiercely seasonal cooking. It's the modern bistro generation, kids, get with it.

From breakfast-friendly cinnamon buns or brown butter fried eggs to caramelised celeriac ravioli, the dishes here are carefully thought out, inventive and delicious, with chefs not being afraid to put lesser known veggies or offal on the plate. As for the drinks, there's a banging selection of well chosen natural wine on offer, with some orange wine, some sweet wine, and tons of fine whisky too.

text.text:
With the team behind Brixton's fine-dining favourite, Salon, on this one, you can be sure the food will be tippity top. The relaxed, hipstery-farmhouse aesthetic remains along with natural wine and menus led by fiercely seasonal cooking. The breakfast menu is teeny tiny, but gorgeous nonetheless. Go for museum quality pastries or decadent brown butter fried eggs, with sourdough toast, lemon and thyme.

The damage: Fried eggs, sourdough toast, confit bacon Â£9.50

listing.subtitle: Roastry â¢ Bakery â¢ Small Plate

tip.text: St John's is a bit of a London institution, very British, very meaty and very well respected amongst those who know. In the abattoir chic setting, dine your way through an indulgent selection of small plates, wholesome breads and quality wines. With a meaty reputation on the line at their sister venues, these guys couldn't help but throw a few of their specials on the menu at this bakery - braised hare; and swede and partridge, with red onion and bread sauce, to name a couple.

text.text:
St John's is quite something, very British, very meaty and very well respected amongst those who know. Dinner is seen to with an indulgent selection of small plates, wholesome breads and quality wines, but for breakfast and you'll see a straight-laced and mighty meaty menu featuring their famous bacon sandwich, devilled kidneys or the v retro kippers on toast. 

The damage: Blood cake, fried egg and brown sauce Â£8.70

tip.text:
Rawduck lays on some quality all-day dining with fresh seasonal produce at the centre of their breakfast, lunch and dinner menus. We've been known to head there for breakfasts of home-made granolas, oats, and egg dishes with middle eastern bread; comforting pasta lunches and more luxurious dinners.

The drinks are just as exciting here with a rotating list of natural and biodynamic wines and house kombuchas, drinking vinegars and kefirs. Blimey that's a lot of fermenting. Over the summer grab an outdoor bench to nibble your raspberry upside down cake with Iranian pistachios and orange blossom yoghurt. Happy days.

text.text:

Their drinks are just as exciting with all sorts of house kombuchas, drinking vinegars and kefirs. Blimey that's a lot of fermenting.

The damage: Fried eggs, coconut rice, chilli sambal, cucumber and peanuts Â£9

tip.text:
Ruth Rogers (actress, puppeteer and founder of the award-winning body-positivity charity Body Gossip) opened Londonâs first happy caf - The Canvas Cafe - meaning it holds all sorts of free events to encourage positive thinking and inspire self-expression. These include relaxation workshops, body confidence classes, documentary screenings and a drop-in choir. You can even write your own positive message on the walls. If all that fails, their vegan bottomless brunch should make you smile.

Hearty grub like tofish and chips, pulled jackfruit sandwiches, no-meatball subs, homemade cakes and vegan 'freakshakes'. Add coffee from Square Mile roasters and you've pretty much all you need for a quick bite or a morning curled up with your laptop.

text.text:
Londonâs first 'happy caf' is an all-vegan operation. As if that wasn't godly enough it also holds all sorts of free events to encourage positive thinking and inspire self-expression: relaxation workshops, body confidence classes, documentary screenings and a drop-in choir. With Square Mile coffee, Â£5 specials and all sorts of comforting vegetables available you should leave feeling just tip top. 

The damage: Full vegan brekkie Â£8.50

tip.text:
Pretty weird to find a cafe that still has the original wood paneling and art deco touch these days, but this proper East End caff does. E. Pellicci serves up no-nonsense grub - fry ups, minestrone, bread pudding - with that kind of food and some of the loveliest staff around, this family owned cafe is pretty much a miracle hangover cure.

The food is comforting but it's the warm welcome that keeps us coming back. It's been in the same family since the 1900s, and the food is still lovingly prepared by mamma and served by her kiddies. Aww.

text.text:
A bit of an institution in these parts, E. Pellicci serves up no-nonsense Italian and fry ups a'plenty. It's pretty much a miracle hangover cure. The food is comforting but it's the warm welcome that keeps us coming back. It's been in the same family since the 1900s, and the food is still lovingly prepared by mamma and served by her kiddies. Aww.

The damage: Full English Â£7.80

tip.text:
'Oh it wasn't like this in my day...' You may have heard about the sad demise of the classic British caff, and maybe thought you didn't care. That was until you stumbled upon one like this, in your hour of need, and they replenished you with a fry-up like no other.

Andrew's Restaurant is a good option, with plenty of original features (think formica tables and sturdy wooden chairs). Food-wise, they're keeping things simple with a strong selection of full English brekkies, hot jacky ps and fresh sarnies. And the tea? It comes piping hot, the colour of brick, in a mug, and with a smile.

tip.text:
Yeah, yeah, yeah, everyone knows about Beigel Bake - after all it is a Brick Lane institution and the bees knees of bagels. The shop is open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week so you can get your bagel fix round the clock. They serve their rings of dough traditional Jewish-style with fillings such as salmon and cream cheese, chopped herring, and salami. And all these come in below the Â£2 mark, which is an absolutely bargain.

The speciality, however, is the hot salt beef with mustard and pickles, and it'll set you back a relatively steep Â£4.50. But for the amount of salt beef they cram into that bad boy, it still feels like a deal. Just be prepared to queue, these bagels are famous and will draw a crowd.

They serve their rings of dough traditional Jewish-style with fillings such as salmon and cream cheese, chopped herring, and salami.
